We investigate how CLIP-semantic information manifests in 
Wonder3D's intermediate UNet features during the denoising 
process. For each of 30 GSO test objects, we run Wonder3D 
inference with 50 DDIM steps and extract feature activations 
at three decoder blocks (up_blocks[1,2,3]) both before 
(PRE-CD) and after (POST-CD) the cross-domain attention 
module. At each timestep, we compute Linear CKA between the 
front-view feature representation and the input image's CLIP 
embedding, across all 30 objects (bootstrap 95% CI, n=1000).

Figure X shows CKA curves for all 6 block-location 
combinations. Three observations emerge:

1. CLIP information persists throughout denoising. CKA 
   values remain stable across all 50 timesteps without 
   significant drift, ranging from 0.36 (deep post-CD) to 
   0.86 (shallow pre/post-CD).

2. Shallow decoder blocks encode CLIP more strongly than 
   deep blocks. up_blocks[1] consistently achieves CKA ≈ 
   0.83-0.86, while up_blocks[3] drops to 0.36-0.50. This 
   is consistent with standard observations that shallow 
   features capture abstract semantic content while deeper 
   features handle local/textural details.

3. Cross-domain attention slightly shifts CKA: shallow 
   features (up_blocks[1,2]) maintain high alignment 
   post-CD, while deep features (up_blocks[3]) drop 
   slightly post-CD — suggesting cross-domain attention 
   introduces geometry information from the normal stream 
   that trades off against CLIP-semantic alignment at 
   fine-grained levels.

These findings support the design of our perception-guided 
readout framework: Wonder3D features reliably encode 
extractable CLIP-semantic information, making readout 
heads feasible. Our CaptionHead operates on shallow 
post-CD features where CLIP alignment is highest.